"""
╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║          OPERATOR CONDITIONS REPORT GENERATOR — DESIGN DOCUMENT            ║
║          HydroOne / IESO E-log  ·  Mistral 7B Q4_K  ·  llama-cpp          ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

PURPOSE
───────
Reads the IESO E-log Excel file, classifies each event log entry by severity,
and generates a structured operator conditions report for shift handover.
Designed to run entirely on a low-RAM laptop (CPU-only, no GPU required).

PROBLEM CONSTRAINTS
───────────────────
• Source data  : 20,000–85,000 log rows per day in Excel
• Hardware     : Low-RAM laptop, CPU only (no GPU)
• Model        : Mistral 7B Instruct Q4_K_M via llama-cpp-python (~4.1 GB)
• Latency      : Per-entry LLM calls on full set = 22+ hours → not viable
• Solution     : Map-Reduce funnel — LLM only sees ~5–10% of rows

ARCHITECTURE — MAP-REDUCE PIPELINE
────────────────────────────────────

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  Excel E-log  (20k–85k rows/day)                        │
  └───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                      │ load_elog() + filter_shift()
                      ▼
  ══════════════ MAP PHASE ════════════════════════════════
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  TIER 1 — RULE ENGINE          (pandas, ~0s)            │
  │  • COMPLETED=Y + routine code  → SKIP, no LLM          │
  │  • Known HIGH_CODES            → flag as candidate      │
  │  • SKIP_ALL_COMPLETED=True     → any completed → skip   │
  │  Eliminates ~80% of rows                                │
  └───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                      ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  TIER 2 — KEYWORD TRIAGE       (regex, ~0s)             │
  │  • HIGH_KEYWORDS match         → flag as candidate      │
  │  • ROUTINE_KEYWORDS match      → SKIP, no LLM          │
  │  Eliminates ~50% of tier 1 survivors                    │
  └───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                      │ ~5–10% of original rows survive
                      ▼
  ══════════════ STEP 1: analyze_entry.prompty ════════════
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  LLM PASS 1 — PER-RECORD SUMMARISATION (batched)        │
  │  Every candidate record (Tier 1 flagged + Tier 2        │
  │  flagged + ambiguous) goes through analyze_entry        │
  │  prompt. Produces per-record structured JSON:           │
  │    should_include, summary (1-2 sentences),             │
  │    priority (CRITICAL/HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW),                 │
  │    ieso_notified, ieso_notification_time                │
  │  • Batched 10 per prompt for throughput                 │
  │  • GBNF grammar enforces JSON structure token-by-token  │
  │  • No parse failures possible with grammar              │
  └───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                      │ only should_include=True records
                      ▼
  ══════════════ REDUCE PHASE ═════════════════════════════
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  build_entries_string()                                 │
  │  Formats included records as the {{entries}} variable   │
  │  matching executive_summary.prompty contract:           │
  │    [CRITICAL] ts | equip | sector                       │
  │      Summary: <llm 1-2 sentence summary>                │
  │    [HIGH] ...                                           │
  │    [MEDIUM] ... (summary only)                          │
  │    [LOW] ... (equipment + code only)                    │
  └───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                      ▼
  ══════════════ STEP 2: executive_summary.prompty ════════
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  LLM PASS 2 — EXECUTIVE SUMMARY (single Reduce call)   │
  │  Reads the pre-formatted {{entries}} string and writes  │
  │  a professional handover report:                        │
  │  • MANDATORY: IESO notifications stated first           │
  │  • Opens with shift status: normal/eventful/critical    │
  │  • CRITICAL + HIGH: listed individually with equip name │
  │  • MEDIUM: single sentence with count                   │
  │  • LOW: brief count only                                │
  │  • 4-6 sentences, plain prose, no bullet points         │
  │  • temperature=0.2, max_tokens=600                      │
  └───────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                      ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  OUTPUT                                                 │
  │  reports/conditions_report_<ts>.txt                     │
  │  logs/conditions_<ts>.log                               │
  │  logs/audit_<ts>.csv                                    │
  │  dev/<ts>/00–08_*  (DEV_MODE only)                      │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

WHY EVERY CANDIDATE GOES THROUGH analyze_entry (Step 1)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Tier 1 and Tier 2 tell us WHICH records to include — they cannot produce
the 1-2 sentence operational summary the executive_summary prompt needs.
A code label ("AUTOMATIC OUTAGE event on Midtown TLM") is not a summary.
The Reduce phase needs consistent LLM-generated summaries for all included
records, regardless of which tier flagged them, so the executive summary
LLM always reads structured, comparable input.

GBNF GRAMMAR (v7 addition)
───────────────────────────
GBNF (GGML Backus-Naur Form) constrains the model's token sampling so it
is physically impossible to output invalid JSON. Eliminates all parse
failures and retries. Defined as a formal grammar passed to llama-cpp via
the `grammar` parameter. The grammar enforces:
  • Exact JSON array structure
  • All required fields present
  • priority restricted to CRITICAL | HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW
  • boolean fields are true/false only
  • ieso_notification_time is quoted string or null

LOW-RAM OPTIMISATIONS
─────────────────────
• n_ctx=4096, n_batch=512   — 512 balances prefill speed vs RAM (per Map-Reduce doc)
• f16_kv=True               — halves KV cache memory vs f32
• logits_all=False          — only compute logits for last token (faster)
• embedding=False           — disable embedding layer (not needed)
• use_mmap=True             — model weights memory-mapped, OS pages on demand
• use_mlock=False           — allows OS to swap if needed
• No <s> in prompt strings  — llama-cpp injects BOS token automatically
• del llm; gc.collect()     — explicitly free model RAM between passes
• n_threads=4               — match to physical cores, NOT logical/hyperthreaded

PROMPT ENGINEERING (Mistral 7B Instruct)
─────────────────────────────────────────
Mistral uses [INST]...[/INST] with NO system role — all in one block.
Rules:
  1. Role at top of [INST] block
  2. One-shot JSON array example (format demonstration > description)
  3. Untrusted data in <comment> XML tags with injection warning at point of data
  4. "JSON array:" at very end (recency bias for greedy decode start)
  5. temperature=0.0 + top_k=1 for Step 1 JSON (deterministic)
  6. temperature=0.2 + top_k=40 for Step 2 prose (coherent but not robotic)
  7. GBNF grammar for Step 1 — no repeat_penalty needed on JSON output

DATA CLEANING
─────────────
• Whitespace normalised; N/A/NAN/NONE → empty
• Control characters stripped (Unicode Cc/Cf)
• Event codes uppercased
• MAX_COMMENT_CHARS applied for LLM input (keeps prompts short)
• Full raw comment preserved separately — never modified

CONFIGURATION (top of file)
────────────────────────────
  MODEL_PATH, EXCEL_PATH, SHEET_NAME
  SHIFT_START_HOUR, SHIFT_END_HOUR, SHIFT_DATE
  LLM_BATCH_SIZE     records per analyze_entry batch (default 10)
  MAX_COMMENT_CHARS  comment truncation for LLM input (default 400)
  SKIP_ALL_COMPLETED True = skip COMPLETED=Y non-HIGH without LLM
  N_THREADS          match to physical CPU cores
  N_BATCH            512 = fast prefill; reduce to 128 if OOM
  DEV_MODE           True = write intermediate artifacts to ./dev/

DEPENDENCIES
────────────
  pip install llama-cpp-python pandas openpyxl
  Model: https://huggingface.co/TheBloke/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2-GGUF
         mistral-7b-instruct-v0.2.Q4_K_M.gguf  (~4.1 GB)

VERSION HISTORY
───────────────
  v1  Basic per-shift LLM summarisation
  v2  Per-entry JSON analysis (Elog Architecture paper)
  v3  Fixed Mistral prompt format, token budgets, low-RAM settings
  v4  3-tier funnel for 20k+ records; batch LLM pass
  v5  Structured logging, stage timers, audit CSV
  v6  DEV_MODE intermediate artifact writing
  v7  GBNF grammar (no parse failures); correct two-step pipeline —
      ALL candidates through analyze_entry (Step 1) then executive
      summary Reduce pass (Step 2); f16_kv, logits_all, embedding flags;
      build_entries_string() as standalone {{entries}} contract;
      MAX_COMMENT_CHARS raised to 400; n_batch=512
"""

